<bill id="DLM3025302" in.amend="false" irdnumbering="no" official="yes" xml:lang="en-NZ" year.imprint="2010" bill.no="169" bill.type="government" stage="2" year="2010">
  <billdetail>
    <title>Education Amendment Bill (No 2)</title>
    <billtype>Government Bill</billtype>
    <repnote>As reported from the Education and Science Committee</repnote>
    <commentary id="DLM3332400" in.amend="false" irdnumbering="no" official="yes" bill.no="169" bill.type="government" stage="2" year="2010">
      <heading>Commentary</heading>
      <comm.lev1>
        <heading>Recommendation</heading>
        <para>
          <text>The Education and Science Committee has examined the Education Amendment Bill (No 2) and recommends by majority that it be passed with the amendments shown.</text>
        </para>
      </comm.lev1>
      <comm.lev1>
        <heading>Introduction</heading>
        <para>
          <text>This bill seeks to amend the Education Act 1989. It includes provisions concerned with four broad policy areas.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>The bill would provide a legislative framework for secondary-tertiary programmes. It would update and clarify the law affecting private schools by implementing the majority of the recommendations of the 2009 Law Commission report, <emphasis style="italic">Private Schools and the Law</emphasis>. It would change the refund provisions for international students enrolled in private training establishments to improve the financial sustainability of New Zealand’s export education market. It would exempt limited-attendance centres from early childhood education licensing standards to make it easier for recreation facilities, shopping centres, and similar organisations to provide short-term childcare.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>The bill would also make policy changes to school enrolment scheme priorities for out-of-zone students by giving some priority to children of board members and of former pupils.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>This commentary covers the major amendments that we recommend.</text>
        </para>
      </comm.lev1>
      <comm.lev1>
        <heading>Secondary-tertiary programmes</heading>
        <para>
          <text>We recommend that the new definition of <quote.in>tertiary component</quote.in> that would be inserted in section 2(1) by clause 4 be amended; and that new section 31G in clause 10 be amended. These two amendments would remove Industry Training Organisations from the lists of providers of components of secondary-tertiary programmes. Industry Training Organisations may not directly provide secondary or tertiary education under current legislation; their role is to arrange elements of tertiary study, usually with Private Training Establishments, and we consider that this should remain unchanged.</text>
        </para>
      </comm.lev1>
      <comm.lev1>
        <heading>Private schools</heading>
        <comm.lev2>
          <heading>Provisional registration</heading>
          <para>
            <text>We recommend that new sections 35A and 35I in clause 11 be amended to allow the Secretary for Education the option of requesting further Education Review Office (ERO) reports during extensions to the provisional registration of private schools, and to allow the Secretary to consider these reports before deciding on full registration of a private school.</text>
          </para>
        </comm.lev2>
        <comm.lev2>
          <heading>Review costs</heading>
          <para>
            <text>We recommend that clause 11 be amended by removing new section 35J. This would remove a requirement for ERO to charge private schools with more than 29 foreign students a proportion of review costs. ERO does not use the section in the principal Act which the new section would replace, and estimates that the cost of enforcing the new section would barely be covered by any revenue collected.</text>
          </para>
        </comm.lev2>
        <comm.lev2>
          <heading>Suspension of registration</heading>
          <para>
            <text>We recommend amending new sections 35K and 35M in clause 11. This would clarify that the Secretary could suspend a private school’s registration only alongside at least one other sanction of those detailed in new sections 35K(2)(a), (b), and (c).</text>
          </para>
        </comm.lev2>
      </comm.lev1>
      <comm.lev1>
        <heading>New Zealand Teachers Council</heading>
        <comm.lev2>
          <heading>Data matching</heading>
          <para>
            <text>We recommend that new clause 12A be inserted to amend section 128A of the principal Act. This would allow the Ministry of Education and the New Zealand Teachers Council to match data on relieving teachers, who were unintentionally excluded from the data matching provisions of the Education Amendment Act 2010.</text>
          </para>
        </comm.lev2>
        <comm.lev2>
          <heading>Interim suspensions</heading>
          <para>
            <text>We recommend that new clause 12C be inserted to amend section 139AU of the principal Act, and that new clause 12D be inserted to make a consequential amendment to section 139AUA. This would ensure that an interim suspension of the practising certificate of a teacher could be made in appropriate circumstances. It would allow the Complaints Assessment Committee of the Teachers Council to apply to the Chair of the Disciplinary Tribunal of the Teachers Council for an interim suspension as a consequence of either a mandatory report or a complaint. It would also clarify that such a suspension could be applied for at any time between the Teachers Council becoming aware of a complaint or report, and the matter being resolved.</text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>Current legislation is unclear about the rights or obligations of an employer to continue to employ or to dismiss a teacher whose practising certificate is suspended. The possibility has been raised that employers may, under current legislation, be committing an offence if they continue to employ a teacher whose registration has been suspended.</text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>It is our intention that a teacher who has had an interim suspension imposed on their practising certificate should be suspended from teaching (with pay continuing as appropriate), and that the Ministry of Education should provide funding for relieving staff as appropriate for teachers at State and State integrated schools, but that no other obligation would be placed on the employer with regard to continuing to employ or dismissing the teacher.</text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>We were assured that the Government will address any issues this provision might raise in respect of other legislation.</text>
          </para>
        </comm.lev2>
        <comm.lev2>
          <heading>Allowing action following a mandatory report</heading>
          <para>
            <text>We recommend inserting new clause 12F to repeal subsection (8) of section 139AZC of the principal Act, and inserting new clause 12G to insert new sections 139AZCA and 139AZCB. We recommend that new sections 12B and 12E be inserted to make consequential amendments. This would allow the Teachers Council to take action following the receipt of a mandatory report relating to a teacher’s competence. The legislation currently allows action following the receipt of a complaint regarding competence; we consider that it was intended to also allow action following the receipt of a mandatory report, for which our recommended amendment would provide.</text>
          </para>
        </comm.lev2>
        <comm.lev2>
          <heading>Annotation of the teachers register</heading>
          <para>
            <text>Proposed new section 139AZCB(a)(iii), to be inserted by new clause 12G, would allow the Teachers Council, if it were satisfied that a teacher had not attained the required level of competence, to annotate the teachers register where the council had imposed conditions on a teacher’s practising certificate.</text>
          </para>
        </comm.lev2>
      </comm.lev1>
      <comm.lev1>
        <heading>Private Training Establishment refund provisions</heading>
        <para>
          <text>We recommend amending clause 16(4) to substitute a new section 236A(2). This would ensure that any payments made by a foreign student enrolled in a course shorter than three months at a Private Training Establishment would be held in trust, and would be available for refund to the student in accordance with the statutory refund scheme. Payments made by long-term domestic and foreign students at such establishments are already treated this way.</text>
        </para>
      </comm.lev1>
      <comm.lev1>
        <heading>Limited-attendance centres</heading>
        <para>
          <text>We recommend that new clause 18(2) be inserted to amend section 310(3) to allow limited-attendance centres that look after the children of employees to be treated in the same way as other limited-attendance centres.</text>
        </para>
      </comm.lev1>
      <comm.lev1>
        <heading>New Zealand Labour Party minority view</heading>
        <para>
          <text>Labour members believe this bill goes too far in removing regulation from limited-attendance centres providing childcare.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>We were informed by officials that this bill will remove the requirement for police checks of those employed by limited-attendance centres and the only regulations that will apply are general building regulations as required by local authorities.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>Labour members are concerned that the resulting lack of regulation leaves children vulnerable and that there should be sufficient regulations in place for these centre to give parents and caregivers assurances about the safety of care and protection of children who attend limited-attendance centres.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>Labour members are concerned that the Government has not accepted many of the recommendations of the Law Commission on independent schools, and has thereby left students in those schools subject to poor teaching and administrative practices.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>We are very opposed to the changes to zoning rules and especially to the concept that entry to a New Zealand State school is an inherited right. It is our view that this cuts across the long-accepted New Zealand concept that locals should be given priority entry to State schools when roll limits are reached, and we are of a view that in the medium term some schools will reduce their zones in order to make places for these <quote.in>inheritance students</quote.in>.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>While we support the late Supplementary Order Paper of the minister in relation to the Teachers’ Council we regret the process she has used and the fact that she has not used the opportunity to clarify the name suppression issues which are leading to many innocent teachers being under a cloud of suspicion, when the naming of the teacher subject to a hearing and the suppressing of the name of other parties is a preferable alternative.</text>
        </para>
      </comm.lev1>
      <comm.lev1>
        <heading>Green Party minority view</heading>
        <para>
          <text>The Green Party member is opposing this bill because despite some useful clauses, it contains some provisions which we and some submitters have sought and failed to modify. Therefore we are unable to change our position on this bill.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>The secondary-tertiary programmes development is generally positive for students but we have strong opposition to at least two of the other major parts of the bill.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>The clauses related to <quote.in>limited-attendance</quote.in> early childhood centres fail to provide proper safety and protection for babies and small children. Issues such as police vetting, staff ratios per child, proximity of parents, plus health and safety standards in places where infants are cared for are being ignored. This has been very disappointing for the Green member of the select committee, who was hoping for some reasonable amendments which she could support.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>The private schools provisions have been controversial for some submitters and not all the Law Commission suggestions from the review of the area have been adopted, notably the appeal provisions for parents of expelled students. Therefore this may be an opportunity lost for a serious review of private school issues.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>The school enrolment provisions that give priority to children of board members and of former pupils over other out-of-zone students are totally unacceptable. Public schools for all children should not be undermined by prioritising board members’ children or former pupils’ children in their out-of-zone priority lists. We view this as a human rights issue.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>We are also opposed to the late amendments that change the powers of the Teachers Council interim suspension provisions for teachers, not as a point of principle but because of the process. We are concerned about the coherence of this bill and this amendment is yet another extraneous issue added to the list. The New Zealand Educational Institute as a last-minute submitter made the valid point that there may well be good reasons for strengthening and clarifying the interim suspension procedures and options, but that for teachers to feel justice has been done this issue should be given proper investigation. We are not convinced that we face a crisis at this time requiring this amendment. We are persuaded that in the long term it needs to be clarified to protect the interests of students and of staff.</text>
        </para>
      </comm.lev1>
      <comm.appendix>
        <heading>Appendix</heading>
        <comm.lev2>
          <heading>Committee process</heading>
          <para>
            <text>The Education Amendment Bill (No 2) was referred to the committee on 30 June 2010. The closing date for submissions was 6 August 2010. We received and considered 18 submissions from interested groups and individuals. We heard nine submissions.</text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text/>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>On 18 October 2010 we received proposed amendments from the Minister of Education which would affect the New Zealand Teachers Council. We agreed to consider the amendments alongside the main bill, and presented an interim report to the House on 20 October 2010. We sought and heard four further submissions on these amendments from affected parties.</text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>We received advice from the Ministry of Education.</text>
          </para>
        </comm.lev2>
        <comm.lev2>
          <heading>Committee membership</heading>
          <para>
            <text>Allan Peachey (Chairperson)</text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>Catherine Delahunty</text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>Hon Sir Roger Douglas (to 8 September 2010)</text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>Jo Goodhew</text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>Colin King</text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>Hon Trevor Mallard</text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>Sue Moroney</text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>Hon Heather Roy (from 8 September 2010)</text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>David Shearer</text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>Louise Upston</text>
          </para>
        </comm.lev2>
      </comm.appendix>
    </commentary>
